{"title_page": "Binghamton (ferryboat)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Binghamton Ferry.JPG\n|Ship caption=''Binghamton'' at Edgewater, New Jersey\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Ship name=''Binghamton''\n|Ship operator=Hoboken Ferry Co., subsidiary of DL&W RR\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[Newport News Shipbuilding and Drydock Company]]\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=1904\n|Ship launched=February 20, 1905\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship identification=\n|Hide header=\n|Ship flag=\n|Ship owner=\n|Ship registry=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship maiden voyage=\n|Ship in service=April 3, 1905\n|Ship out of service=November 22, 1967\n|Ship fate=Sold for restaurant conversion, 1969\n|Ship status=Restaurant / nightclub (closed/dismantled), Edgewater, NJ\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship tonnage=1,462 gt\n|Ship displacement=\n|Ship length={{convert|231|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam=\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draft={{convert|10.5|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship decks=\n|Ship deck clearance=\n|Ship ramps=\n|Ship power=\n|Ship propulsion=Double-compound reciprocating steam engine having four cylinders, rated 1,400 horsepower, taking steam from two coal-fired single-end Scotch boilers (removed) at 150 lbs working pressure, and driving a screw-propeller at each end on continuous shafting\n|Ship speed=\n|Ship capacity=986 passengers (plus vehicles)\n|Ship crew=\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship nickname\n}}\n{{Infobox NRHP |embed=yes | name =Ferryboat ''Binghamton''\n  | nrhp_type =\n  | image =\n  | caption =\n  | location= 725 River Rd, [[Edgewater, New Jersey]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|40|49|10|N|73|58|33|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = USA New Jersey Bergen County#New Jersey#USA\n  | area =\n| built =1904-05\n| architect= Gardner & Cox\n| architecture=\nJuly 9, 1982<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref>\n | governing_body = Private\n | refnum=82003262<ref name=\"nrhp\">{{cite web|url=http://nrhp.focus.nps.gov/natregsearchresult.do?fullresult=true&recordid=32|title=National Register of Historic Places Listings|accessdate=February 25, 2010}}</ref>\n  | designated_other1_name = New Jersey Register of Historic Places\n  | designated_other1_abbr = NJRHP\n  | designated_other1_link = New Jersey Register of Historic Places\n  | designated_other1_date = May 11, 1982\n  | designated_other1_number = 464<ref name=NJRHP>{{cite web|title=New Jersey and National Registers of Historic Places - Bergen County |url=http://www.state.nj.us/dep/hpo/1identify/lists/bergen.pdf |publisher=[[New Jersey Department of Environmental Protection]] - Historic Preservation Office |page=19 |date=July 7, 2009 |accessdate=February 25, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081030005640/http://www.state.nj.us/dep/hpo/1identify/lists/bergen.pdf |archivedate=October 30, 2008 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n  | designated_other1_num_position = bottom\n  | designated_other1_color = #ffc94b\n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''''Binghamton''''' was a ferryboat that transported passengers across the [[Hudson River]] between [[Manhattan]] and [[Hoboken, New Jersey|Hoboken]] from 1905 to 1967.<ref name=\"Kilgannon 2016\">{{cite news |author=Corey Kilgannon |title=Final Departure for 111-Year-Old Hudson Ferryboat |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/27/nyregion/binghamton-hudson-river-ferryboat.html?hp&action=click&pgtype=Homepage&clickSource=story-heading&module=nygeo-promo-region&region=nygeo-promo-region&WT.nav=nygeo-promo-region&_r=0 |quote= |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 27, 2016 }}</ref> Moored in 1971 at [[Edgewater, New Jersey|Edgewater]], [[Bergen County, New Jersey|Bergen County]], [[New Jersey]], United States, the ship was operated as a [[floating restaurant]] from 1975 to 2007.<ref name=\"Kilgannon 2016\" /> In 2017, following years of damage that effectively rendered the boat unrestorable, the ferry was dismantled.  No structural components were salvaged.<ref name=\"northjersey26july2017\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.northjersey.com/story/news/bergen/edgewater/2017/07/26/demolition-historic-binghamton-ferry-begins/509823001/ |title=Demolition of historic Binghamton ferry begins |last=Shkolnikova |first=Svetlana |date=July 26, 2017 |work=northjersey.com |access-date=July 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''Binghamton'' was built for the [[Delaware, Lackawanna & Western Railroad]]'s Hoboken Ferry Company to carry 986 passengers and their vehicles.<ref>[http://www.bergencountyhistory.org/pdfs/MarkerBooklet100707.pdf Bergen County Historical Society Historic Site Markers]. Accessed January 7, 2009.</ref> Added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on July 9, 1982, the ''Binghamton'' was possibly the last surviving steam ferry built to serve [[New York Harbor]], where commercial steam navigation and double-ended steam ferries got their start, and which was profoundly shaped by vessels of this kind.\n<!--The Binghamton is currently for sale: http://www.boats.com/power-boats/1905-newport-news-shipbuilding-hoboken-ferry-company-binghamton-5762455/#.Vzt4AEzD_cs-->\n\n==Background==\n[[File:John Stevens of Hoboken.jpg|thumb|120px|left|[[John Stevens (inventor, born 1749)|John Stevens]] of Hoboken inaugurated the world's first steam ferry service between Hoboken and Manhattan in 1811.]]\nUntil the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] built [[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|Pennsylvania Station]] in [[Manhattan]] and tunneled under the [[Hudson River]], all New York-bound rail lines from the west terminated at the New Jersey shoreline of [[New York Harbor]]. Accordingly, a number of independent and railroad-affiliated ferry companies provided passenger and light freight service across the harbor. One particular type of ferryboat, the \"double-ender,\" was especially common in New York Harbor.\n\n[[Steamboat|Steam navigation]] met its first commercial success in New York Harbor, with the voyage of [[Robert Fulton]]'s [[North River Steamboat]] (Clermont) from New York to Albany in 1807.  Four years later, in 1811, [[John Stevens (inventor, born 1749)|John Stevens]] inaugurated what is thought to be the world's first steam ferry service on the Hudson River between Hoboken and Manhattan with the vessel ''Juliana''.  The first American double-ended ferries appeared the following year with the paddle-wheelers ''Jersey'' and ''York'' of [[Robert Fulton]]'s York & Jersey Steamboat Ferry Company.<ref name=\"Hilton\">{{cite book |last1=Hilton |first1=George Woodman |title=The illustrated history of paddle steamers |date=1976 |location=New York |isbn=9780846703518 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/illustratedhisto0000hilt/page/73 73-76] |url=https://archive.org/details/illustratedhisto0000hilt/page/73 }}</ref> Excellent for transporting vehicles, the double-enders were well adapted to New York Harbor, where there was considerable demand for speed and efficiency (vehicles could drive on and off from either end, and time-consuming turns were not necessary). It has been estimated that over 400 double-ended ferries operated in New York Harbor during the nineteenth and twentieth centuries. The peak years were 1906-1908 when approximately 150 double-ended ferries were in service in the Harbor.<ref name=\"Hilton\" />\n\nThe Hoboken Ferry Company was a subsidiary of the [[Delaware, Lackawanna and Western Railroad]] (DL&W). The company had a fleet of six ferryboats when it ceased operations in 1967.  These vessels took their names from principal stations on the DL&W RR's main line from Hoboken, NJ to Buffalo, NY.  Three of these - the ''Elmira'', ''Scranton'', and ''Pocono'' (n\u00e9e ''Scandinavia'') - the ''Binghamton'''s sisters, were also built in 1905. (Another, the ''Ithaca'', was destroyed by fire in 1946.) Of these, the ''Binghamton'' is now the only survivor.\n\nThe Binghamton's engine: 4 cylinder, double compound, marine steam engine.  Like the double ended ferryboat Binghamton, this engine is of an axially symmetric design.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://i154.photobucket.com/albums/s240/kellygail/dcompoundsmall.jpg|title=Double expansion engine|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> Double [[compound engine]]<nowiki/>s were superseded by more efficient [[Steam engine|Triple expansion]] steam engines.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Lackawanna EL Logos.JPG|thumb|180px|left|The ''Binghamton'' wore the funnel markings of the [[Lackawanna Railroad|DL&W]] (left) before 1960 and of the [[Erie Lackawanna|Erie-Lackawanna RR]] (right) at the end of her career.]]\nThe ''Binghamton'' (Hull #49) was one of five identical screw-propeller, double-ended ferryboats built by the [[Northrop Grumman Shipbuilding Newport News|Newport News Shipbuilding and Dry-dock Company]] \nat [[Newport News, Virginia]] in 1904\u201305 to designs by Gardner & Cox, naval architects. She was launched on February 20, 1905, with Miss Charlotte Emery, daughter of John M. Emery, the newly promoted superintendent of the Hoboken Ferry Company and Ferry Department of the DL&W, serving as her sponsor. The ''Binghamton'' was completed a month later and left the Newport News yard on March 25 for the trip to Hoboken, New Jersey. She was placed in commission on April 3. Her Captain for the first crossing was Oren D. Relyea.\n\nHer normal run was from the [[Hoboken Terminal]] to Barclay Street, a twelve-minute journey of approximately 1 and 3/4 miles, a trip made continuously nearly every day for more than sixty years (on occasion she substituted on the Hoboken - 23rd Street run).\n\nAs alternate methods of travel across the Harbor were implemented, ferry transport diminished. The opening of the Pennsylvania Railroad line to Penn Station in Manhattan (1907); the [[Port Authority Trans-Hudson|Hudson and Manhattan Rapid Transit Line]] (1907); the [[Holland Tunnel|Holland]] and [[Lincoln Tunnel|Lincoln]] tunnels (1927; 1937); and the [[George Washington Bridge]] (1931) all contributed to the decline of the ferries. In 1960, the DL&W RR merged with the Erie Railroad to form the [[Erie Lackawanna Railway|Erie-Lackawanna Railroad]].  The last ferry crossing of the Hoboken company, in operation since 1821, took place on November 22, 1967, when the railroad closed its trans-Hudson operations and offered its ferries for sale.  The Erie-Lackawanna Railroad eventually filed for bankruptcy before being absorbed into [[Consolidated Rail Corporation|Conrail]] in 1976.\n\nHudson River ferry service later experienced a revival, beginning with services provided by [[NY Waterway]] in December 1986.  These services are maintained by small, single-ended diesel-powered pedestrian ferries that carry on the tradition of their steam-powered predecessors.  Traditional double-ended ferries (diesel-powered) meanwhile continue to serve in New York Harbor on the [[Staten Island Ferry]].\n\n==Appearance on film==\nIn 1948, Marathon Pictures released a crime drama titled [[Close-Up (1948 film)|''Close-Up'']]. A \"B\" production, it was shot entirely in Manhattan. The film includes a dramatic pursuit scene shot outside of the Hoboken Ferry terminal, at Barclay Street, and on board the ferryboat ''Binghamton'' itself. Detailed interiors and exteriors of the ferryboat appear in this scene, as well as passengers and deckhands. The film starred [[Alan Baxter (actor)|Alan Baxter]].\n\n==Restaurant conversion==\n[[File:Binghamton plaque.JPG|thumb|220px|left|The ''Binghamton'' retired in 1967.]]\nThe ''Binghamton'' was acquired in 1969 by Edward Russo, an Edgewater, NJ contractor, for conversion into a restaurant. Russo planned large dining rooms on the Upper and Main decks, plus two pubs in the former engine room.  He leased a berth at Edgewater, NJ, and scheduled a grand opening for Labor Day, 1970.  But a tug strike and delays in dredging her berth at Edgewater indefinitely postponed these plans.<ref name=\"Cotterell 1982\">Cotterell, Harry Jr.  \"Ferryboat Binghamton, Edgewater, Bergen County, New Jersey.\"  National Register of Historic Places Inventory - Nomination Form,  February 1982.</ref>\n\nThe ''Binghamton'' finally moved to Edgewater in 1971.  Unable to find a concessionaire to operate the restaurant, Russo relinquished control of the vessel in 1973.  In late 1974, the ''Binghamton'' was sold to Ferry Binghamton Inc., of Hackensack, New Jersey, for conversion to a restaurant and nightclub.  On February 28, 1975, her new owners had the vessel moved to a new permanent berth about one half mile downstream.  The restaurant opened later that year.<ref name=\"Cotterell 1982\"/>\n\nThe US Department of the Interior listed the ''Binghamton'' on the National Register of Historic Places in 1982. In 1997 the vessel made headlines when its owner, tycoon and former New Jersey Assembly Speaker [[Nelson G. Gross|Nelson Gross]], was found murdered in Manhattan.<ref>Herszenhorn, David M.  \"3 Teen-Agers Plead Guilty in Businessman's Killing.\" ''The New York Times'', February 11, 1998.</ref>  The restaurant, known as \"Binghamton's\", remained in business for ten years, but closed by Fall 2007. The Binghamton remained unused at her berth in Edgewater since then.  In July 2011 the owner applied for a demolition permit.<ref>{{cite web|last=Almenas |first=Maxim |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/98581229_Riverfront__A_path_to_nowhere.html |title=Edgewater riverfront: a path to no where |publisher=NorthJersey.com |date=July 16, 2010 |accessdate=June 7, 2013}}</ref> As of May 2012, the ferry had taken on water and was partially submerged. It was further swamped during Hurricane Sandy on October 29 or 30, 2012.\n\nThe ferry had a fire on Sunday, May 19, 2013, that was investigated by the Edgewater Police and the Bergen County arson squad.  The owner, Daniel Kim, said that there was no damage to the boat.  He further stated that he was closing on a deal to have a subtenant demolish and remove the ferry from the site, with plans to open a restaurant on a barge at that location.<ref>{{cite web|last=Koloff |first=Abbott |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/Bergen_County_arson_squad_investigates_weekend_fire_at_Edgewaters_Binghamton_Ferry.html?page=all |title=Bergen County arson squad investigates weekend fire at Edgewater's Binghamton Ferry |publisher=NorthJersey.com |date=May 23, 2012 |accessdate=June 7, 2013}}</ref> Demolition was expected to start in December 2016 <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nj.com/bergen/index.ssf/2016/11/historic_ferryboats_111-year_journey_coming_to_sad_end.html|title=Historic ferryboat's 111-year journey coming to sad end|newspaper=NJ.com|access-date=2016-11-30}}</ref> and completed by Summer 2017. A replacement floating restaurant, named ''Binghamton II'', was scheduled to open in Summer 2018, but as of today no progress has been made for the future restaurant.<ref>{{cite news |title=Owner: Hudson River Eyesore Be Replaced By New Edgewater Hot Spot |url=https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2017/02/17/edgewater-binghamton/ |accessdate=2018-08-26 |work=CBS New York |date=17 February 2017 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn July 26, 2017, the dismantling of the ferry began.  Efforts to save the pilot houses were in vain when the demolition crew damaged the pilot houses in the process of removing them from the ferryboat's roof.<ref name=\"northjersey26july2017\" />\n\n==Gallery==\nThe ''Binghamton'' at Edgewater, NJ. Photos by T.E. Rinaldi, September 2004.\n<gallery>\nImage:Rinaldi-Binghamton-2004.09.23-01-BW.jpg\nImage:Rinaldi-Binghamton-2004.09.23-06-BW-edit.jpg\nImage:Rinaldi-Binghamton-2004.09.23-09-BW.jpg\nImage:Rinaldi-Binghamton-2004.09.23-07-BW.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n<gallery>\nImage:Rinaldi-Binghamton-2004.09.23-08-BW.jpg\nImage:Rinaldi-Binghamton-2004.09.23-11-BW.jpg\nImage:Rinaldi-Binghamton-2004.09.23-15-BW.jpg\nImage:Rinaldi-Binghamton-2004.09.23-16-BW.jpg\n</gallery>\n\nThe ''Binghamton'' in May 2012\n<gallery>\nImage:Ferry_Binghamton_Partially_Submerged_May_2012.jpg\nImage:Rear_of_Ferry_Binghampton_in_Edgewater_New_Jersey._Partially_Submerged_in_May_2012.jpg\n</gallery>\n\nThe ''Binghamton'' in June 2015\n<gallery>\nImage:Wreck_of_Ferry_Binghamton_June_2015_from_water.jpg\n</gallery>\n\nThe ''Binghamton'' in June 2017, the week of its removal\n<gallery>\nImage:Binghamton 19 June 2017.jpg\nImage:Binghamton Removal 30 June 2017.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Delaware, Lackawanna and Western Railroad]]\n* [[Hoboken Terminal]]\n* [[Erie Railroad]]\n* [[Erie Lackawanna Railway]]\n* [[Robert Fulton]]\n* [[John Stevens (inventor, born 1749)|John Stevens (inventor)]]\n* [[Eureka (ferryboat)]]\n* [[Berkeley (ferryboat)]]\n* [[Hudson River Waterfront Walkway]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Bergen County, New Jersey]]\n* [[List of ferries across the Hudson River to New York City]]\n\n== Further reading ==\n*Adams, Arthur G. and Raymond J. Baxter.  ''Railroad ferries of the Hudson: and stories of a deckhand''.  New York: Fordham University Press, 1999.\n*Cudahy, Brian J. ''Over and back: the history of ferryboats in New York Harbor''. New York: Fordham University Press, 1990.\n*Scull, Theodore W. ''Hoboken's Lackawanna Terminal''.  New York:  Quadrant Press, 1986.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Commons category|Binghamton (ship, 1905)}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.flickr.com/photos/mets1958/1515004355/ Historic photo of the ''Binghamton'' in service at Flickr.]\n*http://www.nnapprentice.com/alumni/letter/BINGHAMTON_%20NNS_Hull_49.pdf\n*http://shipbuildinghistory.com/shipyards/large/newportnews.htm\n\n{{Registered Historic Places}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Binghamton (Ferryboat)}}\n[[Category:Edgewater, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Ferries of New Jersey]]\n[[Category:1905 ships]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Bergen County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Delaware, Lackawanna and Western Railroad]]\n[[Category:New Jersey Register of Historic Places]]\n[[Category:Ships on the National Register of Historic Places in New Jersey]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Binghamton Ferry.JPG\n|Ship caption=''Binghamton'' at Edgewater, New Jersey\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Ship name=''Binghamton''\n|Ship operator=Hoboken Ferry Co., subsidiary of DL&W RR\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[Newport News Shipbuilding and Drydock Company]]\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=1904\n|Ship launched=February 20, 1905\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship identification=\n|Hide header=\n|Ship flag=\n|Ship owner=\n|Ship registry=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship maiden voyage=\n|Ship in service=April 3, 1905\n|Ship out of service=November 22, 1967\n|Ship fate=Sold for restaurant conversion, 1969\n|Ship status=Restaurant / nightclub (closed/dismantled), Edgewater, NJ\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship tonnage=1,462 gt\n|Ship displacement=\n|Ship length={{convert|231|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam=\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draft={{convert|10.5|ft|m|1|abbr=on}}\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship decks=\n|Ship deck clearance=\n|Ship ramps=\n|Ship power=\n|Ship propulsion=Double-compound reciprocating steam engine having four cylinders, rated 1,400 horsepower, taking steam from two coal-fired single-end Scotch boilers (removed) at 150 lbs working pressure, and driving a screw-propeller at each end on continuous shafting\n|Ship speed=\n|Ship capacity=986 passengers (plus vehicles)\n|Ship crew=\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship nickname\n}}\n{{Infobox NRHP |embed=yes | name =Ferryboat ''Binghamton''\n  | nrhp_type =\n  | image =\n  | caption =\n  | location= 725 River Rd, [[Edgewater, New Jersey]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|40|49|10|N|73|58|33|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = USA New Jersey Bergen County#New Jersey#USA\n  | area =\n| built =1904-05\n| architect= Gardner & Cox\n| architecture=\nJuly 9, 1982<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref>\n | governing_body = Private\n | refnum=82003262<ref name=\"nrhp\">{{cite web|url=http://nrhp.focus.nps.gov/natregsearchresult.do?fullresult=true&recordid=32|title=National Register of Historic Places Listings|accessdate=February 25, 2010}}</ref>\n  | designated_other1_name = New Jersey Register of Historic Places\n  | designated_other1_abbr = NJRHP\n  | designated_other1_link = New Jersey Register of Historic Places\n  | designated_other1_date = May 11, 1982\n  | designated_other1_number = 464<ref name=NJRHP>{{cite web|title=New Jersey and National Registers of Historic Places - Bergen County |url=http://www.state.nj.us/dep/hpo/1identify/lists/bergen.pdf |publisher=[[New Jersey Department of Environmental Protection]] - Historic Preservation Office |page=19 |date=July 7, 2009 |accessdate=February 25, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081030005640/http://www.state.nj.us/dep/hpo/1identify/lists/bergen.pdf |archivedate=October 30, 2008 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n  | designated_other1_num_position = bottom\n  | designated_other1_color = #ffc94b\n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''''Binghamton''''' was a ferryboat that transported passengers across the [[Hudson River]] between [[Manhattan]] and [[Hoboken, New Jersey|Hoboken]] from 1905 to 1967.<ref name=\"Kilgannon 2016\">{{cite news |author=Corey Kilgannon |title=Final Departure for 111-Year-Old Hudson Ferryboat |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/27/nyregion/binghamton-hudson-river-ferryboat.html?hp&action=click&pgtype=Homepage&clickSource=story-heading&module=nygeo-promo-region&region=nygeo-promo-region&WT.nav=nygeo-promo-region&_r=0 |quote= |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 27, 2016 }}</ref> Moored in 1971 at [[Edgewater, New Jersey|Edgewater]], [[Bergen County, New Jersey|Bergen County]], [[New Jersey]], United States, the ship was operated as a [[floating restaurant]] from 1975 to 2007.<ref name=\"Kilgannon 2016\" /> In 2017, following years of damage that effectively rendered the boat unrestorable, the ferry was dismantled.  No structural components were salvaged.<ref name=\"northjersey26july2017\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.northjersey.com/story/news/bergen/edgewater/2017/07/26/demolition-historic-binghamton-ferry-begins/509823001/ |title=Demolition of historic Binghamton ferry begins |last=Shkolnikova |first=Svetlana |date=July 26, 2017 |work=northjersey.com |access-date=July 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''Binghamton'' was built for the [[Delaware, Lackawanna & Western Railroad]]'s Hoboken Ferry Company to carry 986 passengers and their vehicles.<ref>[http://www.bergencountyhistory.org/pdfs/MarkerBooklet100707.pdf Bergen County Historical Society Historic Site Markers]. Accessed January 7, 2009.</ref> Added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on July 9, 1982, the ''Binghamton'' was possibly the last surviving steam ferry built to serve [[New York Harbor]], where commercial steam navigation and double-ended steam ferries got their start, and which was profoundly shaped by vessels of this kind.\n<!--The Binghamton is currently for sale: http://www.boats.com/power-boats/1905-newport-news-shipbuilding-hoboken-ferry-company-binghamton-5762455/#.Vzt4AEzD_cs-->\n\n==Background==\n[[File:John Stevens of Hoboken.jpg|thumb|120px|left|[[John Stevens (inventor, born 1749)|John Stevens]] of Hoboken inaugurated the world's first steam ferry service between Hoboken and Manhattan in 1811.]]\nUntil the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] built [[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|Pennsylvania Station]] in [[Manhattan]] and tunneled under the [[Hudson River]], all New York-bound rail lines from the west terminated at the New Jersey shoreline of [[New York Harbor]]. Accordingly, a number of independent and railroad-affiliated ferry companies provided passenger and light freight service across the harbor. One particular type of ferryboat, the \"double-ender,\" was especially common in New York Harbor.\n\n[[Steamboat|Steam navigation]] met its first commercial success in New York Harbor, with the voyage of [[Robert Fulton]]'s [[North River Steamboat]] (Clermont) from New York to Albany in 1807.  Four years later, in 1811, [[John Stevens (inventor, born 1749)|John Stevens]] inaugurated what is thought to be the world's first steam ferry service on the Hudson River between Hoboken and Manhattan with the vessel ''Juliana''.  The first American double-ended ferries appeared the following year with the paddle-wheelers ''Jersey'' and ''York'' of [[Robert Fulton]]'s York & Jersey Steamboat Ferry Company.<ref name=\"Hilton\">{{cite book |last1=Hilton |first1=George Woodman |title=The illustrated history of paddle steamers |date=1976 |location=New York |isbn=9780846703518 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/illustratedhisto0000hilt/page/73 73-76] |url=https://archive.org/details/illustratedhisto0000hilt/page/73 }}</ref> Excellent for transporting vehicles, the double-enders were well adapted to New York Harbor, where there was considerable demand for speed and efficiency (vehicles could drive on and off from either end, and time-consuming turns were not necessary). It has been estimated that over 400 double-ended ferries operated in New York Harbor during the nineteenth and twentieth centuries. The peak years were 1906-1908 when approximately 150 double-ended ferries were in service in the Harbor.<ref name=\"Hilton\" />\n\nThe Hoboken Ferry Company was a subsidiary of the [[Delaware, Lackawanna and Western Railroad]] (DL&W). The company had a fleet of six ferryboats when it ceased operations in 1967.  These vessels took their names from principal stations on the DL&W RR's main line from Hoboken, NJ to Buffalo, NY.  Three of these - the ''Elmira'', ''Scranton'', and ''Pocono'' (n\u00e9e ''Scandinavia'') - the ''Binghamton'''s sisters, were also built in 1905. (Another, the ''Ithaca'', was destroyed by fire in 1946.) Of these, the ''Binghamton'' is now the only survivor.\n\nThe Binghamton's engine: 4 cylinder, double compound, marine steam engine.  Like the double ended ferryboat Binghamton, this engine is of an axially symmetric design.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://i154.photobucket.com/albums/s240/kellygail/dcompoundsmall.jpg|title=Double expansion engine|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> Double [[compound engine]]<nowiki/>s were superseded by more efficient [[Steam engine|Triple expansion]] steam engines.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Lackawanna EL Logos.JPG|thumb|180px|left|The ''Binghamton'' wore the funnel markings of the [[Lackawanna Railroad|DL&W]] (left) before 1960 and of the [[Erie Lackawanna|Erie-Lackawanna RR]] (right) at the end of her career.]]\nThe ''Binghamton'' (Hull #49) was one of five identical screw-propeller, double-ended ferryboats built by the [[Northrop Grumman Shipbuilding Newport News|Newport News Shipbuilding and Dry-dock Company]] \nat [[Newport News, Virginia]] in 1904\u201305 to designs by Gardner & Cox, naval architects. She was launched on February 20, 1905, with Miss Charlotte Emery, daughter of John M. Emery, the newly promoted superintendent of the Hoboken Ferry Company and Ferry Department of the DL&W, serving as her sponsor. The ''Binghamton'' was completed a month later and left the Newport News yard on March 25 for the trip to Hoboken, New Jersey. She was placed in commission on April 3. Her Captain for the first crossing was Oren D. Relyea.\n\nHer normal run was from the [[Hoboken Terminal]] to Barclay Street, a twelve-minute journey of approximately 1 and 3/4 miles, a trip made continuously nearly every day for more than sixty years (on occasion she substituted on the Hoboken - 23rd Street run).\n\nAs alternate methods of travel across the Harbor were implemented, ferry transport diminished. The opening of the Pennsylvania Railroad line to Penn Station in Manhattan (1907); the [[Port Authority Trans-Hudson|Hudson and Manhattan Rapid Transit Line]] (1907); the [[Holland Tunnel|Holland]] and [[Lincoln Tunnel|Lincoln]] tunnels (1927; 1937); and the [[George Washington Bridge]] (1931) all contributed to the decline of the ferries. In 1960, the DL&W RR merged with the Erie Railroad to form the [[Erie Lackawanna Railway|Erie-Lackawanna Railroad]].  The last ferry crossing of the Hoboken company, in operation since 1821, took place on November 22, 1967, when the railroad closed its trans-Hudson operations and offered its ferries for sale.  The Erie-Lackawanna Railroad eventually filed for bankruptcy before being absorbed into [[Consolidated Rail Corporation|Conrail]] in 1976.\n\nHudson River ferry service later experienced a revival, beginning with services provided by [[NY Waterway]] in December 1986.  These services are maintained by small, single-ended diesel-powered pedestrian ferries that carry on the tradition of their steam-powered predecessors.  Traditional double-ended ferries (diesel-powered) meanwhile continue to serve in New York Harbor on the [[Staten Island Ferry]].\n\n==Appearance on film==\nIn 1948, Marathon Pictures released a crime drama titled [[Close-Up (1948 film)|''Close-Up'']]. A \"B\" production, it was shot entirely in Manhattan. The film includes a dramatic pursuit scene shot outside of the Hoboken Ferry terminal, at Barclay Street, and on board the ferryboat ''Binghamton'' itself. Detailed interiors and exteriors of the ferryboat appear in this scene, as well as passengers and deckhands. The film starred [[Alan Baxter (actor)|Alan Baxter]].\n\n==Restaurant conversion==\n[[File:Binghamton plaque.JPG|thumb|220px|left|The ''Binghamton'' retired in 1967.]]\nThe ''Binghamton'' was acquired in 1969 by Edward Russo, an Edgewater, NJ contractor, for conversion into a restaurant. Russo planned large dining rooms on the Upper and Main decks, plus two pubs in the former engine room.  He leased a berth at Edgewater, NJ, and scheduled a grand opening for Labor Day, 1970.  But a tug strike and delays in dredging her berth at Edgewater indefinitely postponed these plans.<ref name=\"Cotterell 1982\">Cotterell, Harry Jr.  \"Ferryboat Binghamton, Edgewater, Bergen County, New Jersey.\"  National Register of Historic Places Inventory - Nomination Form,  February 1982.</ref>\n\nThe ''Binghamton'' finally moved to Edgewater in 1971.  Unable to find a concessionaire to operate the restaurant, Russo relinquished control of the vessel in 1973.  In late 1974, the ''Binghamton'' was sold to Ferry Binghamton Inc., of Hackensack, New Jersey, for conversion to a restaurant and nightclub.  On February 28, 1975, her new owners had the vessel moved to a new permanent berth about one half mile downstream.  The restaurant opened later that year.<ref name=\"Cotterell 1982\"/>\n\nThe US Department of the Interior listed the ''Binghamton'' on the National Register of Historic Places in 1982. In 1997 the vessel made headlines when its owner, tycoon and former New Jersey Assembly Speaker [[Nelson G. Gross|Nelson Gross]], was found murdered in Manhattan.<ref>Herszenhorn, David M.  \"3 Teen-Agers Plead Guilty in Businessman's Killing.\" ''The New York Times'', February 11, 1998.</ref>  The restaurant, known as \"Binghamton's\", remained in buisness for ten years, but closed by Fall 2007. The Binghamton remained unused at her berth in Edgewater since then.  In July 2011 the owner applied for a demolition permit.<ref>{{cite web|last=Almenas |first=Maxim |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/98581229_Riverfront__A_path_to_nowhere.html |title=Edgewater riverfront: a path to no where |publisher=NorthJersey.com |date=July 16, 2010 |accessdate=June 7, 2013}}</ref> As of May 2012, the ferry had taken on water and was partially submerged. It was further swamped during Hurricane Sandy on October 29 or 30, 2012.\n\nThe ferry had a fire on Sunday, May 19, 2013, that was investigated by the Edgewater Police and the Bergen County arson squad.  The owner, Daniel Kim, said that there was no damage to the boat.  He further stated that he was closing on a deal to have a subtenant demolish and remove the ferry from the site, with plans to open a restaurant on a barge at that location.<ref>{{cite web|last=Koloff |first=Abbott |url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/Bergen_County_arson_squad_investigates_weekend_fire_at_Edgewaters_Binghamton_Ferry.html?page=all |title=Bergen County arson squad investigates weekend fire at Edgewater's Binghamton Ferry |publisher=NorthJersey.com |date=May 23, 2012 |accessdate=June 7, 2013}}</ref> Demolition was expected to start in December 2016 <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nj.com/bergen/index.ssf/2016/11/historic_ferryboats_111-year_journey_coming_to_sad_end.html|title=Historic ferryboat's 111-year journey coming to sad end|newspaper=NJ.com|access-date=2016-11-30}}</ref> and completed by Summer 2017. A replacement floating restaurant, named ''Binghamton II'', was scheduled to open in Summer 2018, but as of today no progress has been made for the future restaurant.<ref>{{cite news |title=Owner: Hudson River Eyesore Be Replaced By New Edgewater Hot Spot |url=https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2017/02/17/edgewater-binghamton/ |accessdate=2018-08-26 |work=CBS New York |date=17 February 2017 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn July 26, 2017, the dismantling of the ferry began.  Efforts to save the pilot houses were in vain when the demolition crew damaged the pilot houses in the process of removing them from the ferryboat's roof.<ref name=\"northjersey26july2017\" />\n\n==Gallery==\nThe ''Binghamton'' at Edgewater, NJ. Photos by T.E. Rinaldi, September 2004.\n<gallery>\nImage:Rinaldi-Binghamton-2004.09.23-01-BW.jpg\nImage:Rinaldi-Binghamton-2004.09.23-06-BW-edit.jpg\nImage:Rinaldi-Binghamton-2004.09.23-09-BW.jpg\nImage:Rinaldi-Binghamton-2004.09.23-07-BW.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n<gallery>\nImage:Rinaldi-Binghamton-2004.09.23-08-BW.jpg\nImage:Rinaldi-Binghamton-2004.09.23-11-BW.jpg\nImage:Rinaldi-Binghamton-2004.09.23-15-BW.jpg\nImage:Rinaldi-Binghamton-2004.09.23-16-BW.jpg\n</gallery>